arch:property.oc:show_val: Construction of the East Walkway Wall and the pavement of the East Walkway.

Phase IV: Nabataean Grand Design: 1st c. BCE to CE 1st c. The tetrastyle in antis temple is built, including the Porch extension, stylobate, Porch columns, East, West and South Corridor walls, East and West Walkway Walls and the East and West Porch Antae. Additionally, the limestone flooring from Phase II is extended at this time to cover the surfaces of the new corridors and walkways.

This floor is composed of limestone slabs of irregular size. Extant portions follow the eastern side of the East Corridor Wall in the north. In the southwestern portion of the Walkway, the floor also extends eastward. The floor is arranged in an alternating stretcher-header pattern. The average size of each header is 0.52 m-by-0.52 m. Stretchers, however, are either 0.80 or 1.00 m in length-by-0.52 m in width. Many of stones are missing in the northern and central portion of walkway.
